SECTION 1: AI Agent Meta-Rules

NO EXPLANATIONS: Do not explain code, patterns, or decisions unless explicitly asked. I know what I'm doing.
NO CONTEXTUAL COMMENTS: Do not add useless comments like "// Making a request with include" or "// Validating payload".
DOMAIN COMMENTS ALLOWED: You MAY add comments about missing critical business logic.
PLAN-EXECUTE FLOW: For complex features, first provide a bulleted plan of changes. Wait for confirmation before generating code.

SECTION 2: Backend Standards (.NET 10, FastEndpoints, EF Core)
Architecture: Vertical Slice Architecture (VSA)

The folders Configuration, Domain, Infrastructure are for SHARED concerns only.
All new application logic MUST go inside /Features/{SliceName}. A slice contains everything: the Endpoint, the internal logic (if small), Request/Response DTOs, and Validators.
Tech Stack & Patterns:
Target Framework: .NET 10 (Latest C# features).
API Style: Minimal APIs using FastEndpoints.
Result Pattern: Enforce the pattern defined in Domain/Common/Result.cs. Endpoints must return our custom Result<T>.
CRITICAL FIX (FastEndpoints Responses): Do NOT use FastEndpoints typed responses (e.g., SendOkAsync<TResponse>). Instead, you MUST manually map our Result<T> to FastEndpoints SendAsync(dto, status) to ensure our standard error structure is maintained.
DTOs & Data Transfer:
Requests/Responses: Prefer C# Records for all DTOs and immutable messages. Convert existing classes to records during refactoring.
Projections: Never use AutoMapper. Use EF Core projections (Select(x => new DTO { ... })) directly on IQueryable to maximize performance.
Domain & Constraints:
IHasStatus: All entities must implement IHasStatus. Use the EntityStatus enum (1: SinActivar, 2: Activo, 3: Borrado). Global query filters MUST exclude Borrado (3) by default, but allow SinActivar (1) and Activo (2).
Common Utilities: Prefer methods in Domain/Common (Pagination, SemestreHelper, etc.).
Constants & Roles: Use the Roles defined in Constants; do not query a nonexistent Roles table.
Claims Handling: CRITICAL: Do not parse Claims manually in endpoints. Always use the extension methods provided in Infrastructure/Extensions/UserExtensions.cs.

SECTION 3: Frontend Standards (Angular 21, PrimeNG 21, Tailwind 4)
Tech Stack:

Framework: Angular 21 (latest features, signals, standalone).
CSS: Tailwind CSS 4 (tw4).
UI Lib: PrimeNG 21 (Aura theme).
Styling & Design:
Color Palette: Predominantly Blue (TecNM standard).
UI Reuse: Never implement local Toasts or ProgressBars. Use the global implementations.
NO NATIVE UI DIALOGS: Using native alert(), confirm(), or prompt() is strictly forbidden. Use PrimeNG's ConfirmationService, MessageService (Toasts), or the Signal-based custom Dialog component implemented in the app.
Aesthetics Consistency: Maintain style symmetry between similar components (e.g., Tables must look identical across features).
Architecture & Optimization:
Variables: Use English for all naming.
Constants: Retrieve endpoints from the existing Constants file.
Interceptors: Respect existing interceptors in core/interceptors for security (CSRF, credentials) and loading.
Badges/Status: Use the existing Status utility for rendering badges. Back-end sends raw status; front-end handles mapping to PrimeNG colors/labels.
STATE MANAGEMENT: Use Signals for all local component state. No more raw variables for reactive data.
INPUTS: Use the input() or input.required() API. Never use the @Input() decorator.
OUTPUTS: Use the output() API. Never use the @Output() decorator or EventEmitter.
TWO-WAY BINDING: Use the model() API for properties that require two-way data binding (like a search term or a toggle status).
EFFECTS/COMPUTED: Use computed() for derived state (e.g., filtering a list based on a signal search term) and effect() only when performing side effects (like logging or manual DOM manipulation).
TEMPLATE ACCESS: Use the signal getter syntax in templates: {{ mySignal() }}.

SECTION 4: Specific Problem Resolutions
CRITICAL FIX: Modal/Tab Lazy Loading (Angular)
When generating multi-tab components (e.g., in features\alumnos\detail), DO NOT PRE-RENDER TABS.VSA Requirement for Tabs: When using PrimeNG Tabs, you MUST use dynamic component loading with @if or p-tabPanel lazy rendering so a network call to fetch data only triggers when the user actually clicks the tab. Never load all N tabs on open.